{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dc88cf50-183b-4bdb-ab2d-4273a5f45ee8","content":"\n\nRun **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — reinstalls the **same versions** already recorded. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installs but won't pull newer versions needed by a newer SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK changed → versions are mismatched → you need `update`, not `repair`.\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf it still fails afterward, try a clean restore:\n\n```bash\ndotnet clean && dotnet restore\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d2491833-bc2f-44fa-8258-a7b9181e3b1b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":244},"id":"8e68b99f-248b-42bd-9bb1-cc1b3db46e14","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:41:51.446Z","parentId":"e1528bfb-c93a-4986-bcfc-6ab76ce253f5"}
